<subSubSection id="C34EA1DDFFE51807FF770DC3FDDBFADD" pageId="95" pageNumber="96" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="8BEBF256FFE51807FF770DC3FF5EFB81" blockId="95.[151,1437,397,1181]" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">
<emphasis id="B9202E44FFE51807FF770DC3FE18FCC5" bold="true" box="[199,424,757,784]" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">Biology and notes.</emphasis>
Although the 
<emphasis id="B9202E44FFE51807FDE30DC0FC8CFCC5" box="[595,828,758,784]" italics="true" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">Systema Dipterorum</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFC58FA7FFE51807FCFD0DC0FBDCFCC5" author="Thompson, F. C. &amp; Pape, T" box="[845,1132,758,784]" pageId="95" pageNumber="96" refId="ref141080" refString="Thompson, F. C. &amp; Pape, T (2010) Systema Dipterorum. http: // www. diptera. org / (accessed 20 May 2018)" type="url" year="2010">Thompson &amp; Pape 2010</bibRefCitation>
) reports 
<taxonomicName id="4C5489D5FFE51807FB650DC0FA2CFCC5" authorityName="Hull" authorityYear="1936" box="[1237,1436,758,784]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Tachinosyrphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="95" pageNumber="96" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pseudotachina">
<emphasis id="B9202E44FFE51807FB650DC0FA2CFCC5" box="[1237,1436,758,784]" italics="true" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">C. pseudotachina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingCountry id="F343B2C6FFE51807FF070C2CFF46FCE1" box="[183,246,794,820]" name="Chile" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">Chile</collectingCountry>
, we did not find any article that confirms that this species occurs in the country. Therefore, we treated this species as a new to 
<collectingCountry id="F343B2C6FFE51807FE180C08FE58FC8D" box="[424,488,830,856]" name="Chile" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">Chile</collectingCountry>
. It is the only known syrphid with bristle-like hairs on the abdomen and bare arista, which is considered a novel trait in the tribe 
<taxonomicName id="4C5489D5FFE51807FD120C54FC45FCA9" authority="(Thompson 1972)" baseAuthorityName="Thompson" baseAuthorityYear="1972" box="[674,1013,866,892]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="95" pageNumber="96" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Volucellini">Volucellini (Thompson 1972)</taxonomicName>
. There are only three records of this species in 
<collectingCountry id="F343B2C6FFE51807FEA20CB0FEE1FC75" box="[274,337,902,928]" name="Chile" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">Chile</collectingCountry>
, all from highlands in the Chilean ‘altiplano’ belonging to the Puna province (
<bibRefCitation id="EFC58FA7FFE51807FB560CB0FA20FC75" author="Morrone, J. J." box="[1254,1424,902,928]" pageId="95" pageNumber="96" pagination="1 - 110" refId="ref135042" refString="Morrone, J. J. (2014) Biogeographical regionalisation of the Neotropical region. Zootaxa, 3782 (1), 1 - 110. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3782.1.1" type="journal article" year="2014">Morrone 2014</bibRefCitation>
), considered a hotspot of biodiversity (Myer 
<emphasis id="B9202E44FFE51807FD340C9DFD0DFC11" box="[644,701,938,964]" italics="true" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">et al.</emphasis>
, 2000). There, this species visits yellow flowers of 
<taxonomicName id="4C5489D5FFE51807FAB90C9CFDBCFC3D" authority="(Meyen) Cabrera" authorityName="Cabrera" authorityYear="1954" baseAuthorityName="Meyen" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Parastrephia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="95" pageNumber="96" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="quadrangularis">
<emphasis id="B9202E44FFE51807FAB90C9CFEF5FC3D" italics="true" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">Parastrephia quadrangularis</emphasis>
(Meyen) Cabrera
</taxonomicName>
(Rodrigo Barahona-Segovia pers. obs.), and 
<taxonomicName id="4C5489D5FFE51807FBB40CF8FEA2FBD9" authority="(Phil.) Lu-Irving &amp; O'Leary" authorityName="Lu-Irving &amp; O'Leary" baseAuthorityName="Phil." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Verbenaceae" genus="Aloysia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="95" pageNumber="96" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="deserticola">
<emphasis id="B9202E44FFE51807FBB40CF8FB6BFC3D" box="[1028,1243,974,1000]" italics="true" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">Aloysia deserticola</emphasis>
(Phil.) Lu-Irving &amp; O’Leary
</taxonomicName>
(Diego Reyes, CSP record), a common plant species that blooms once Bolivian winter is over (
<figureCitation id="136FEED3FFE51807FA9F0CC4FA20FBD9" box="[1327,1424,1010,1036]" captionStart="FIGURES 140–143" captionStartId="96.[151,264,1945,1969]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1073,1922]" captionTargetId="figure-260@96.[151,1436,1073,1922]" captionTargetPageId="96" captionText="FIGURES 140–143. Copestylum willinki (Fluke, 1951): (140) lateral view and (141) dorsal view, female (Photos by Vicente Valdés). (142) Copestylum pseudotachina (Hull, 1936) feeding on Aloysia deserticola (Phil.) Lu-Irving &amp; O’Leary, Socaire (Photo by Diego Reyes). (143) Ornidia obesa (Fabricius, 1775), dorsal view (Photo by Vicente Valdés)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4693580" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4693580/files/figure.png" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">Fig. 142</figureCitation>
). This species has low abundance and is affected by habitat loss due to mining and water exploitation, and climate change.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BEBF256FFE51807FF770B6BFE56FB48" blockId="95.[151,1437,397,1181]" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">
<emphasis id="B9202E44FFE51807FF770B6BFE0FFBAD" bold="true" box="[199,447,1117,1144]" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">Conservation status.</emphasis>
EN under B1ab (iii) + 2ab (iii) using EOO = 
<quantity id="4CAC5FB3FFE51807FC560B68FBE7FBAD" box="[998,1111,1118,1144]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.242" pageId="95" pageNumber="96" unit="km" value="4.242">4,242 km</quantity>
2; AOO = 
<quantity id="4CAC5FB3FFE51807FB640B68FAAFFBAD" box="[1236,1311,1118,1144]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="95" pageNumber="96" unit="km" value="12.0">12 km</quantity>
<superScript id="7C215F1EFFE51807FAAE0B68FA96FBB9" attach="left" box="[1310,1318,1118,1132]" fontSize="6" pageId="95" pageNumber="96">2</superScript>
and three localities (or subpopulations).
</paragraph>
